1
00:00:19,019 --> 00:00:20,379
<i>I could have been a bomb,</i>

2
00:00:20,437 --> 00:00:22,397
<i>I could have been in jail,
I could have been dead.</i>

3
00:00:22,439 --> 00:00:24,524
<i>But I worked my ass off to get here.</i>

4
00:00:33,033 --> 00:00:35,368
<i>You hear a lot of negative things
about Dennis Rodman.</i>

5
00:00:35,827 --> 00:00:37,746
<i>Well, people don't actually know
Dennis Rodman.</i>

6
00:00:37,829 --> 00:00:40,707
<i>They just see what they see on the court
and read in the papers,</i>

7
00:00:40,790 --> 00:00:42,792
<i>and they say, "God, he's a bad person."</i>

8
00:00:44,419 --> 00:00:46,880
Does it hurt you
that the public perceives you

9
00:00:46,963 --> 00:00:49,215
as this bombastic, crazy guy?

10
00:00:50,258 --> 00:00:53,094
No, I just think that
I created this monster.

11
00:00:56,097 --> 00:01:00,018
<i>But, uh, nobody could say anything bad
about me as a teammate.</i>

12
00:01:01,394 --> 00:01:03,104
<i>You got the great Michael Jordan,</i>

13
00:01:03,188 --> 00:01:05,315
<i>the great Scottie Pippen,
the great Phil Jackson,</i>

14
00:01:05,899 --> 00:01:10,278
<i>but if you take me away from this team,
do they still win a championship?</i>

15
00:01:11,946 --> 00:01:13,114
<i>I don't think so.</i>

16
00:01:15,200 --> 00:01:18,745
<i>I love Michael Jordan to death.
I love Scottie Pippen, all these guys,</i>

17
00:01:18,828 --> 00:01:21,372
<i>but they really don't do the things
that I do.</i>

18
00:01:25,543 --> 00:01:27,629
<i>I'm the only guy
who does all the dirty work,</i>

19
00:01:27,712 --> 00:01:29,339
<i>taking abuse from other players.</i>

20
00:01:31,174 --> 00:01:33,843
<i>I wanna go out there
and get my nose broke, I wanna get cut.</i>

21
00:01:35,220 --> 00:01:37,722
<i>Something that's gonna really
just bring out the...</i>

22
00:01:38,598 --> 00:01:40,642
<i>the hurt, the pain.</i>

23
00:01:41,518 --> 00:01:42,644
<i>I wanna feel that.</i>

24
00:01:46,272 --> 00:01:47,774
<i>A spectacular move!</i>

25
00:01:47,857 --> 00:01:49,442
<i>The game's over!</i>

26
00:01:49,526 --> 00:01:51,861
<i>Chicago Stadium is going wild!</i>

27
00:01:53,822 --> 00:01:56,324
<i>First of all,
there's no backstabbing going on here.</i>

28
00:01:56,407 --> 00:01:57,283
<i>It's time for me to move on.</i>

29
00:01:57,367 --> 00:01:59,767
<i>This will be Phil's last year
as coach of the Bulls.</i>

30
00:02:02,372 --> 00:02:04,934
<i>- Are the expectations too high?
- Where do we go from here?</i>

31
00:02:04,958 --> 00:02:07,460
<i>The only question: how long can it last?</i>

32
00:02:23,977 --> 00:02:27,272
<i>They still might be considered
world champs, but so far this season,</i>

33
00:02:27,355 --> 00:02:30,608
<i>the Chicago Bulls have looked more like
that old circus act from the '80s</i>

34
00:02:30,692 --> 00:02:33,111
<i>called "Michael and his Jordanaires."</i>

35
00:02:33,194 --> 00:02:36,406
They need help.
They're reeling, looking average.

36
00:02:36,906 --> 00:02:38,908
<i>As for MJ's supporting cast,</i>

37
00:02:38,992 --> 00:02:41,286
<i>Rodman is having trouble
getting out of the gate.</i>

38
00:02:43,621 --> 00:02:47,167
Michael, are you tired
of talking about Pippen and all that yet?

39
00:02:47,250 --> 00:02:48,334
Pretty much.

40
00:02:49,335 --> 00:02:51,713
Until something happens,
until he says what he's gonna do,

41
00:02:51,796 --> 00:02:53,840
we have to continue on.
We gotta do our jobs.

42
00:02:57,218 --> 00:02:58,469
Let's go, fellas.

43
00:03:00,805 --> 00:03:03,805
<i>First meeting with Michael
the player against Larry the coach.</i>

44
00:03:03,850 --> 00:03:05,643
<i>Bulls and Pacers.</i>

45
00:03:06,895 --> 00:03:08,897
<i>Dennis Rodman, blocked by Dale Davis.</i>

46
00:03:08,980 --> 00:03:10,106
<i>Reggie Miller.</i>

47
00:03:10,732 --> 00:03:13,401
<i>Look at the crossover,
right past Jordan for the hoop.</i>

48
00:03:13,484 --> 00:03:16,029
<i>Phil Jackson, we've seen that look
before this year.</i>

49
00:03:16,112 --> 00:03:18,823
<i>Pacers go on to the win,
dropping the Bulls to 8-7.</i>

50
00:03:18,907 --> 00:03:22,035
<i>Last season, Chicago didn't lose
their seventh until game 56.</i>

51
00:03:22,493 --> 00:03:23,953
We missed a lot of easy shots.

52
00:03:24,037 --> 00:03:25,717
We haven't shot the ball
particularly well.

53
00:03:26,247 --> 00:03:28,917
But, uh, tonight what killed us
was our rebounding.

54
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:30,501
Our rebounding was horrendous.

55
00:03:31,085 --> 00:03:33,366
We couldn't get the rebound,
we couldn't clear the boards.

56
00:03:35,840 --> 00:03:39,928
Dennis is kind of lagging
back there behind everybody else

57
00:03:40,011 --> 00:03:43,097
in, you know,
his enthusiasm for the game right now.

58
00:03:43,890 --> 00:03:46,434
Dennis Rodman's the best on-ball defender

59
00:03:46,517 --> 00:03:49,479
I've ever seen in 30 years.

60
00:03:50,980 --> 00:03:55,944
<i>The problem was that
he wasn't always motivated to play.</i>

61
00:03:56,027 --> 00:03:58,446
It's another one of those periods
that I'm bored as hell.

62
00:03:58,529 --> 00:04:02,242
I gotta find some way
to put a log on the fire.

63
00:04:04,869 --> 00:04:07,247
...that's a low blow down here, right?
Intentional foul.

64
00:04:07,330 --> 00:04:08,581
I didn't see it that way.

65
00:04:09,415 --> 00:04:11,251
There's a lot of things I don't see.

66
00:04:15,421 --> 00:04:17,757
Most of the time, though,
I see the shit you do.

67
00:04:21,970 --> 00:04:23,850
Dennis hadn't accepted
the role that...

68
00:04:24,722 --> 00:04:28,101
Scottie wasn't gonna be around
and we needed you to be more accountable.

69
00:04:28,184 --> 00:04:29,727
I need to count on you.

70
00:04:30,311 --> 00:04:35,358
So, around that time, we had a game,
and he gets kicked out for some shit.

71
00:04:36,484 --> 00:04:39,654
And I'm livid,
because he got kicked out of the game

72
00:04:39,737 --> 00:04:42,657
and leaves me out there by myself
'cause Scottie's not playing.

73
00:04:43,241 --> 00:04:45,994
And Dennis knew he fucked up.
He knew he screwed up.

74
00:04:47,829 --> 00:04:50,456
I hear someone knocking on my door
at the hotel.

75
00:04:51,291 --> 00:04:53,334
Now, Dennis never comes in my room,

76
00:04:53,418 --> 00:04:56,045
and he comes and says,
"Man, you got an extra cigar?"

77
00:04:56,838 --> 00:04:59,340
I went to Michael Jordan's room,
asked for a cigar, but...

78
00:04:59,757 --> 00:05:02,844
But I think that he knew the fact that...

79
00:05:03,386 --> 00:05:04,887
That's probably his way...

80
00:05:04,971 --> 00:05:08,683
Of me showing him that, you know,
"Man, my thing, my bad."

81
00:05:09,684 --> 00:05:11,853
He didn't say an apology,
he didn't say anything,

82
00:05:12,437 --> 00:05:13,813
but by him coming to my room,

83
00:05:13,896 --> 00:05:16,024
it was his way of saying,
"Look, I fucked up."

84
00:05:17,233 --> 00:05:20,236
<i>And from that point on,
Dennis was straight as an arrow.</i>

85
00:05:20,820 --> 00:05:22,238
<i>And we started to win.</i>

86
00:05:22,322 --> 00:05:24,032
I'd like to ask y'all one question.

87
00:05:24,115 --> 00:05:26,451
- What time is it?
- Game time!

88
00:05:36,878 --> 00:05:40,298
When Scottie left, I think
Mike had a lot of confidence in me

89
00:05:40,381 --> 00:05:42,467
to know that I'm gonna be there for him.

90
00:05:42,550 --> 00:05:45,178
I'm not going to let him down,
I'm not going to let the team down,

91
00:05:45,261 --> 00:05:46,846
let the city down. No.

92
00:05:48,973 --> 00:05:51,768
<i>Rodman clears
the defensive board for the Bulls.</i>

93
00:05:54,562 --> 00:05:58,107
<i>Nets gave it a whirl,
but just did not have enough.</i>

94
00:05:58,191 --> 00:06:03,905
<i>The defending champion Chicago Bulls
knocked off the New Jersey Nets 100 to 92.</i>

95
00:06:03,988 --> 00:06:06,699
Dennis is what held us together
when Scottie was out.

96
00:06:07,325 --> 00:06:10,995
He had to really focus to make us
as competitive as we were.

97
00:06:11,954 --> 00:06:15,666
We adapt and we adapt quickly,
and we're off and running.

98
00:06:15,750 --> 00:06:18,920
<i>Rodman,
battling for the rebound, saving it in!</i>

99
00:06:19,003 --> 00:06:21,047
<i>And Kerr snatches it out of the air,</i>

100
00:06:21,589 --> 00:06:22,589
<i>and drills it!</i>

101
00:06:22,632 --> 00:06:25,176
<i>Now that's...
that's winning basketball.</i>

102
00:06:25,259 --> 00:06:30,056
<i>Those are the plays that Dennis Rodman
does to make his team great.</i>

103
00:06:30,681 --> 00:06:31,682
<i>Awesome.</i>

104
00:06:44,404 --> 00:06:47,073
As a black kid
living in the projects,

105
00:06:47,156 --> 00:06:49,992
life was really fucking nuts,
right, it was like... Whoa!

106
00:06:52,703 --> 00:06:54,747
My mother drove buses for the school.

107
00:06:55,248 --> 00:06:58,835
She got sick and tired of my ass
not providing, not doing anything.

108
00:06:58,918 --> 00:07:02,046
And, I think... What was I, 18?

109
00:07:02,588 --> 00:07:04,382
She just got tired of me
and kicked me out

110
00:07:04,465 --> 00:07:06,384
so I lived in the street for two years.

111
00:07:08,177 --> 00:07:10,972
I was just trying to bounce around,
see where I could stay at.

112
00:07:11,931 --> 00:07:14,851
People's backyards, my friends' backyards,
stuff like that.

113
00:07:14,934 --> 00:07:16,978
I could've been a drug dealer,
I could've been dead,

114
00:07:17,061 --> 00:07:19,188
I could've been...
Shit, anything at that time.

115
00:07:20,106 --> 00:07:23,317
I don't know why I never did
that drug stuff, but I never did.

116
00:07:23,860 --> 00:07:27,280
I'd just sit there and watch 'em do it,
watch 'em sell it, stuff like that,

117
00:07:27,363 --> 00:07:29,782
and I walk out the door every day,
go to the gym.

118
00:07:29,866 --> 00:07:32,160
Come back, do the same thing every day.

119
00:07:32,243 --> 00:07:35,663
I was just fortunate to start picking up
a basketball and start playing.

120
00:07:37,748 --> 00:07:39,542
And I just got lucky that

121
00:07:39,625 --> 00:07:42,336
some guy from some college said,
"Dennis, you wanna play for us?"

122
00:07:42,420 --> 00:07:43,796
I was like, "All right, great."

123
00:07:45,798 --> 00:07:49,677
I went balls-out every time. I don't know.
I just know how to go full speed.

124
00:07:50,720 --> 00:07:55,391
So, when I was in college, I averaged,
like, 27 points, 14, 15, rebounds a game.

125
00:08:00,438 --> 00:08:05,568
I'm trying to get through school,
try to get a degree and things,

126
00:08:06,110 --> 00:08:11,240
and whatever's... When I finish school,
I just hope for the best.

127
00:08:11,324 --> 00:08:14,452
We had two other picks in the second round
that I'll give you quickly.

128
00:08:14,535 --> 00:08:16,913
Greg Dreiling went to Indiana,
the big center,

129
00:08:16,996 --> 00:08:20,500
and Dennis Rodman, the youngster
from Southeast Oklahoma State,

130
00:08:20,583 --> 00:08:24,045
went to Detroit
as the 27th pick in the 1986 draft.

131
00:08:25,129 --> 00:08:30,426
When he first came to Detroit,
he was just an innocent, beautiful person,

132
00:08:30,510 --> 00:08:33,888
but a little naive about, like, the world.

133
00:08:34,722 --> 00:08:37,016
He was simple at that time.

134
00:08:37,517 --> 00:08:39,727
He would say, "Man, you don't know life

135
00:08:39,810 --> 00:08:42,688
till you can just go out,
get away from everybody,

136
00:08:43,397 --> 00:08:47,443
make a fire, cook food outside,
and just look at the stars."

137
00:08:49,529 --> 00:08:51,729
I think the second
or third year in the league,

138
00:08:51,781 --> 00:08:55,868
I actually figured out what I can do best:
rebound and play defense.

139
00:08:55,952 --> 00:08:57,995
<i>Barkley, with the drive...</i>

140
00:08:58,079 --> 00:09:00,748
I just started
learning how to perfect that.

141
00:09:00,831 --> 00:09:02,959
<i>Holy cow! How about that?</i>

142
00:09:03,042 --> 00:09:05,044
I used to have my friends late at night,

143
00:09:05,127 --> 00:09:08,881
shit, 3:00, 4:00 in the morning,
go to the gym. I said, "Shoot the ball."

144
00:09:08,965 --> 00:09:11,509
I said, "Shoot over here,
shoot over there..."

145
00:09:11,592 --> 00:09:13,886
I'd just sit there, react, react.

146
00:09:14,887 --> 00:09:18,391
I practiced a lot about the angle
of the ball and trajectory of it.

147
00:09:18,474 --> 00:09:22,395
You got a Larry Bird, it's gonna spin.
You got a Magic, it maybe spin.

148
00:09:22,478 --> 00:09:25,314
When Michael shoot over here,
I position myself right there.

149
00:09:25,398 --> 00:09:27,984
Now if it hit the rim, it's... Boom.

150
00:09:28,067 --> 00:09:30,444
Click and go back this way.
It going here and here.

151
00:09:30,528 --> 00:09:31,696
Click, it going that way.

152
00:09:31,779 --> 00:09:32,822
Boom! That way.

153
00:09:32,905 --> 00:09:34,657
Click here and go this way.

154
00:09:34,740 --> 00:09:38,119
So, basically, I started learning how to
put myself in a position to get the ball.

155
00:09:38,202 --> 00:09:40,663
<i>Rebound,
kept alive by Rodman, and...</i>

156
00:09:41,622 --> 00:09:44,750
I was pretty much like that rash
on players,

157
00:09:44,834 --> 00:09:47,003
that rash you can't
never get rid of, right?

158
00:09:50,840 --> 00:09:55,177
Dennis Rodman was the fuck-up person.
He just fucks everything up.

159
00:09:55,970 --> 00:10:00,057
He's a pest.
Shutting down whoever he wanted to.

160
00:10:00,683 --> 00:10:02,059
It was always a challenge.

161
00:10:02,768 --> 00:10:07,023
He was one of them players that had
changed the game just by his presence.

162
00:10:08,065 --> 00:10:11,694
You talk about coach's dreams,
there aren't many players like him.

163
00:10:11,777 --> 00:10:15,573
Couldn't be a player I'm more proud of
and proud to be associated with.

164
00:10:15,656 --> 00:10:18,159
He had a great relationship
with Chuck Daly.

165
00:10:18,242 --> 00:10:21,078
<i>Chuck was the only person
that understood him.</i>

166
00:10:21,162 --> 00:10:22,455
Let's say your guy stops side,

167
00:10:22,538 --> 00:10:25,082
you're in here,
you're defense, lock him here.

168
00:10:25,166 --> 00:10:27,918
I remember one time,
I was working with Dennis,

169
00:10:28,002 --> 00:10:31,714
and then Chuck called me over,
and he said, "Just leave him alone.

170
00:10:32,715 --> 00:10:34,800
You don't put a saddle on a mustang."

171
00:10:38,929 --> 00:10:41,932
Were you considered
a troublemaker on the court in college?

172
00:10:42,016 --> 00:10:44,977
- Did you have that reputation?
- No. I built that in Detroit.

173
00:10:45,061 --> 00:10:46,646
There's no disputing that Detroit

174
00:10:46,729 --> 00:10:49,398
is one of the most physical teams
in the NBA,

175
00:10:49,482 --> 00:10:51,359
and it's all part of their strategy

176
00:10:51,442 --> 00:10:53,778
to take their opponents
out of their rhythm.

177
00:10:54,737 --> 00:10:57,740
The Detroit Pistons
were the epitome

178
00:10:57,823 --> 00:11:04,205
of the physical, tough,
hard-nosed brand of half-court basketball.

179
00:11:04,288 --> 00:11:11,253
They had big strong guys in Laimbeer,
Mahorn, Rodman, Salley.

180
00:11:11,337 --> 00:11:15,841
They had a great defensive player
in Joe Dumars, they had Isiah Thomas.

181
00:11:16,425 --> 00:11:19,637
Were they threatening
the safety of the league's top players?

182
00:11:20,930 --> 00:11:22,848
I don't think they cared.

183
00:11:24,850 --> 00:11:28,437
<i>Wilkins gets knocked
to the deck, and wants Mahorn.</i>

184
00:11:29,855 --> 00:11:31,232
<i>Rivers...</i>

185
00:11:31,315 --> 00:11:34,276
<i>Pushed hard. I mean,
he was driven to the floor.</i>

186
00:11:35,027 --> 00:11:38,364
At that time, in the NBA,
you could do anything you want.

187
00:11:39,407 --> 00:11:42,451
Compared to today,
30 years ago, shit.

188
00:11:42,535 --> 00:11:46,330
Back then, you could just sit there
and just literally beat people up

189
00:11:46,914 --> 00:11:49,667
and get away with it
without a technical or anything.

190
00:11:49,750 --> 00:11:54,296
<i>Dennis Rodman and Lohaus,
under the basket, going at it.</i>

191
00:11:55,923 --> 00:11:58,634
We're like a hockey team,
everybody wanna see us fight.

192
00:11:58,718 --> 00:12:01,303
Rick Mahorn taught me
how to elbow and said,

193
00:12:01,387 --> 00:12:03,305
"If you hit somebody, do it on purpose.

194
00:12:03,806 --> 00:12:07,351
Don't get a cheap foul. That's stupid.
If you're gonna hit him, hit him."

195
00:12:07,435 --> 00:12:10,438
They acquired the moniker "The Bad Boys."

196
00:12:11,105 --> 00:12:16,277
They played a tough, intimidating style,
and a lot of people didn't like it

197
00:12:16,360 --> 00:12:19,196
'cause it was getting away
from the beauty of basketball.

198
00:12:19,280 --> 00:12:21,824
<i>Bird and Laimbeer go at it.</i>

199
00:12:21,907 --> 00:12:25,244
We weren't "the league's favorite."
We weren't the...

200
00:12:25,327 --> 00:12:29,915
We weren't the pretty team that had got
invited to the Lakers' and Celtics' party.

201
00:12:29,999 --> 00:12:34,170
When we showed up, it was almost like
we were crashing their party.

202
00:12:34,253 --> 00:12:37,214
This is the way the game of basketball
was played at the time.

203
00:12:37,298 --> 00:12:40,301
These guys on the other side
may not be as talented,

204
00:12:40,384 --> 00:12:42,136
but when you do come into Detroit,

205
00:12:42,928 --> 00:12:44,513
you gonna get your ass whooped.

206
00:12:44,597 --> 00:12:47,975
<i>We got a fight.
Laimbeer and Daugherty going after it.</i>

207
00:12:48,851 --> 00:12:51,228
We just basically...
"Okay, we're the bad boys."

208
00:12:51,312 --> 00:12:54,315
We started feeding into it.
Next thing you know, we starting to win.

209
00:12:59,320 --> 00:13:01,614
The Pistons
had overtaken the Celtics

210
00:13:01,697 --> 00:13:03,908
as kings of the Eastern Conference,

211
00:13:03,991 --> 00:13:08,370
and they're rolling along just as
the Bulls are really starting to emerge.

212
00:13:10,247 --> 00:13:13,709
In '86-'87, when Jerry Krause
made a head coaching hire,

213
00:13:14,210 --> 00:13:17,463
I think we all felt that
we needed something different.

214
00:13:18,172 --> 00:13:20,007
This speaks to Jerry's strengths.

215
00:13:20,508 --> 00:13:23,093
He identified a young Doug Collins,

216
00:13:23,177 --> 00:13:28,390
who he felt would bring an energy
and enthusiasm that a young team needed.

217
00:13:28,474 --> 00:13:31,018
This is a game
that we need to have high energy.

218
00:13:31,101 --> 00:13:34,355
We have a high energy level.
We win tonight, we got tomorrow off,

219
00:13:34,438 --> 00:13:37,209
so you can spend all night in LA
doing whatever you want. I don't care.

220
00:13:37,233 --> 00:13:40,194
Otherwise, we got practice tomorrow...

221
00:13:40,277 --> 00:13:42,822
<i>Dougie was a breath of fresh air.</i>

